-- в”Ђв”Ђ Canopy в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Canopy (getcanopy.com) is a cloud-based practice management platform built for accounting, tax, and bookkeeping firms, consolidating client management, workflow automation, document handling, billing, and tax resolution tools into one system. Founded in 2014 by former Wall Street tax attorney Kurt Avarell as Beanstalk before rebranding to Canopy in 2015, it has raised over 290 million dollars in venture funding. Note: a separate, unrelated company called Canopy Connect (usecanopy.com) provides an insurance and banking data API and is not the subject of this profile.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription, per user per month, billed annually or monthly, plus paid add-ons$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$From around 74 dollars per user per month (Standard plan, billed annually)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Mid-size private company; scale not precisely disclosed but backed by over 290 million dollars in total venture funding as of 2025$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Draper, Utah, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Canopy Review 2026: Practice Management Software for Accountants and Tax Firms$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Canopy is an all-in-one practice management platform for accounting and tax firms. See 2026 pricing, features, pros and cons, and how it differs from Canopy Connect.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Canopy is a cloud-based practice management platform built specifically for accounting, tax, and bookkeeping firms in the United States, designed to replace the patchwork of separate tools (CRM, document management, e-signature, billing, workflow, client portal) that many small and mid-sized firms cobble together. The company was founded in March 2014 by Kurt Avarell, a former Wall Street tax attorney who, after taking on pro bono tax resolution cases, became frustrated with how little dedicated software existed for that work and began building the product himself, initially under the name Beanstalk. The company raised 2 million dollars in seed funding from New Enterprise Associates along with EPIC Ventures, Deep Fork Capital, and angel investor Jim Engebretsen, then rebranded from Beanstalk to Canopy in 2015 around the time it raised an 8 million dollar Series A, also led by NEA. Avarell led the company as CEO through its early growth before Davis Bell, a Silicon Slopes technology executive, took over as CEO in December 2019, a leadership change that coincided with a 13 million dollar funding round. Canopy has continued raising capital since, reaching total funding of roughly 292 million dollars, including a 70 million dollar round in April 2025 that the company has been using in part to build out AI-driven features. On the product side, Canopy is organized around three pillars that map to how accounting and tax firms actually operate: an operations layer covering time tracking, billing, payments, and capacity planning; a work management layer covering engagement letters, proposals, automated workflows, and document management; and a client management layer covering a client portal, communications hub, e-signature, and onboarding tools. The company markets itself as holding top ratings on G2 in both accounting practice management and tax practice management categories, and reports that more than 15,000 practitioners use the platform, generating over 250,000 invoices and storing more than 6 million files monthly. It's important to distinguish this Canopy from a similarly-named but unrelated company, Canopy Connect (usecanopy.com), which is an insurance and banking data API sometimes described as Plaid for insurance, used by insurtech and fintech companies to pull structured policy data from carriers. The two companies share only a name; getcanopy.com's Canopy is a practice-management SaaS product for accounting professionals, while Canopy Connect is developer infrastructure for a different industry entirely, and buyers researching either should be careful not to conflate the two when comparing vendors or reading reviews. On pricing, Canopy publishes tiered per-user, per-month rates rather than requiring a sales call for every plan: a Standard tier around 74 dollars per user per month covers CRM, document management, e-signature, client portal, workflow, and basic invoicing; a Plus tier around 109 dollars per user per month adds automated recurring workflows, role-based access controls, and capacity planning; and a Premium tier around 149 dollars per user per month adds deeper automation, advanced billing scenarios, and reporting, with a custom-quoted Enterprise tier above that for larger firms. Add-on modules, including tax workflow automation, close automation, tax resolution, and identity verification (KBA) credits, are priced separately on top of the core subscription, and annual billing saves roughly 20 percent compared to paying monthly.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '23d1542d-9141-41d6-88c7-b79591f12235';

